Analysis: We have followed the prescribed workflow: preprocess (aggregated KPIs/traces/logs), anomaly detection (global P95/P99 per KPI/trace computed on full series), fault identification (found consecutive exceedances in the incident window), and root cause localization (correlating metrics, traces, and logs).

What was done and key evidence:
- Metrics: computed global P95/P99 for all metric KPIs, then inspected 2022-03-21 08:00–08:30 (UTC+8). The top anomalies are overwhelmingly KPIs whose names contain "container.node-5". 34 distinct pods showed node-5 KPI exceedances during the window, with many pods showing earliest exceedances at 08:00.
- Severity/magnitude: the largest relative deviations vs global P95 are node-5 CPU throttling KPIs (container_cpu_cfs_throttled_seconds and container_cpu_cfs_throttled_percent) with extreme max_over_p95_ratio (>1000× and >200× respectively). Other severe deviations include container_cpu_system_seconds and container_cpu_usage_seconds, and very large spikes in container_fs_usage_MB and memory_failures counters. The overall earliest exceedance was at 2022-03-21T08:00:00+08:00 (container.node-5.container_memory_rss on adservice-0), and many node-5 KPIs first breached at or immediately after 08:00.
- Traces: trace.from_frontend-* series show elevated durations/error counts starting at ~08:00 with downstream hotspots at checkoutservice and productcatalogservice; error_logs are concentrated on frontends with many "failed to retrieve..." warnings.

Interpretation per localization rules:
- Multiple components across different services are impacted, and anomalies are concentrated in KPIs explicitly tied to node-5. Because the node-level KPIs show the most significant deviation (>>50% and in many cases hundreds-to-thousands × over P95) compared with any single container/resource KPI at other levels, the root cause level should be node-level.
- Among node-level symptoms, CPU throttling and CPU usage/CPU system seconds show the largest and earliest extreme deviations (first observed at 08:00). Memory and filesystem anomalies are present too but some peak slightly later (e.g., memory failure counters ~08:14, fs usage ~08:11). Traces/logs show frontend errors as downstream effects rather than originating causes.

Derived conclusion: the incident is best explained by a node-level resource issue on node-5 that began at the start of the window (~08:00), dominated by severe CPU contention leading to heavy CPU throttling, with secondary memory and filesystem effects that contributed to application errors observed in traces and logs.
Instruction: Final diagnosis summary (concise):
- Root cause component: node-5
- Root cause occurrence datetime (first observed): 2022-03-21T08:00:00+08:00
- Root cause reason: Node-level CPU saturation leading to severe CPU throttling (high values in container.node-5.container_cpu_cfs_throttled_seconds and container_cpu_cfs_throttled_percent, plus large spikes in container_cpu_system_seconds and container_cpu_usage_seconds). Secondary resource issues (memory failure counters and filesystem usage) also rose within the same window and likely exacerbated failures. These node-level resource anomalies propagated to many containers (including frontend pods), causing elevated trace latencies and frontend error logs.

